   2969          /******** THE REST OF THE FILE IS DOCUMENTATION ONLY !**********************//**
   2970           * @addtogroup uartdrv UARTDRV - UART Driver
   2971           * @brief Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter Driver
   2972           * @{
   2973          
   2974             @details
   2975             The source files for the UART driver library, uartdrv.c and uartdrv.h, are in the
   2976             emdrv/uartdrv folder.
   2977          
   2978             @n @section uartdrv_intro Introduction
   2979             The UART driver supports the UART capabilities of the USART, UART, and LEUART
   2980             peripherals. The driver is fully reentrant and supports multiple driver instances.
   2981             The driver does not buffer or queue data. However, it queues UART transmit
   2982             and receive operations. Both blocking and non-blocking transfer functions are
   2983             available. Non-blocking transfer functions report transfer completion with
   2984             callback functions. Transfers are done using DMA. Simple direct/forced
   2985             transmit and receive functions are also available. Note that these functions
   2986             are blocking and not suitable for low energy applications because they use CPU
   2987             polling.
   2988          
   2989             UART hardware flow control (CTS/RTS) is fully supported by the driver. UART
   2990             software flow control (XON/XOFF) is partially supported by the driver. For
   2991             more information about flow control support, see @ref uartdrv_fc.
   2992          
   2993             @note Transfer completion callback functions are called from within the DMA
   2994             interrupt handler with interrupts disabled.
   2995          
   2996             @n @section uartdrv_conf Configuration Options
   2997          
   2998             Some properties of the UARTDRV driver are compile-time configurable. These
   2999             properties are set in a uartdrv_config.h file. A template for this
   3000             file, containing default values, is in the emdrv/config folder.
   3001             To configure UARTDRV for your application, provide a custom configuration file,
   3002             or override the defines on the compiler command line.
   3003             These are the available configuration parameters with default values defined.
   3004             @code
   3005          
   3006             // Set to 1 to enable hardware flow control.
   3007           #define EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE       1
   3008          
   3009             // Maximum number of driver instances.
   3010           #define EMDRV_UARTDRV_MAX_DRIVER_INSTANCES      4
   3011          
   3012             // UART software flow control code: request peer to start Tx.
   3013           #define UARTDRV_FC_SW_XON                       0x11
   3014          
   3015             // UART software flow control code: request peer to stop Tx.
   3016           #define UARTDRV_FC_SW_XOFF                      0x13
   3017             @endcode
   3018          
   3019             The properties of each UART driver instance are set at run-time via the
   3020             @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t data structure input parameter to the @ref UARTDRV_InitUart()
   3021             function for UART and USART peripherals, and the @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t
   3022             data structure input parameter to the @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart() function for
   3023             LEUART peripherals.
   3024          
   3025             @n @section uartdrv_api The API
   3026          
   3027             This section contains brief descriptions of the functions in the API. For more
   3028             information on input and output parameters and return values,
   3029             click on the hyperlinked function names. Most functions return an error
   3030             code, @ref ECODE_EMDRV_UARTDRV_OK is returned on success,
   3031             see ecode.h and uartdrv.h for other error codes.
   3032          
   3033             The application code must include @em uartdrv.h header file.
   3034          
   3035             @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart() and @ref UARTDRV_DeInit() @n
   3036              These functions initialize and deinitialize the UARTDRV driver. Typically,
   3037              UARTDRV_InitUart() (for UART/USART) or
   3038              UARTDRV_InitLeuart() (for LEUART) are called once in
   3039              the startup code.
   3040          
   3041             @ref UARTDRV_GetReceiveStatus() and @ref UARTDRV_GetTransmitStatus() @n
   3042              Query the status of a current transmit or receive operations. Reports number
   3043              of items (frames) transmitted and remaining.
   3044          
   3045             @ref UARTDRV_GetReceiveDepth() and  @ref UARTDRV_GetTransmitDepth() @n
   3046              Get the number of queued receive or transmit operations.
   3047          
   3048             @ref UARTDRV_Transmit(), UARTDRV_Receive() @n
   3049             UARTDRV_TransmitB(), UARTDRV_ReceiveB() @n
   3050             UARTDRV_ForceTransmit() and UARTDRV_ForceReceive() @n
   3051              Blocking and non-blocking transfer functions are included.
   3052              The blocking versions have an uppercase B (for Blocking) at the end of
   3053              their function name. Blocking functions do not return before the transfer
   3054              is complete. The non-blocking functions signal a transfer completion with a
   3055              callback function. @ref UARTDRV_ForceTransmit() and
   3056              @ref UARTDRV_ForceReceive() are also blocking. These two functions access
   3057              the UART peripheral directly without using DMA or interrupts.
   3058              @ref UARTDRV_ForceTransmit() does not respect flow control.
   3059              @ref UARTDRV_ForceReceive() forces RTS low.
   3060          
   3061             @ref UARTDRV_Abort() @n
   3062              Abort current transmit or receive operations and remove all queued
   3063              operations.
   3064          
   3065             @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet(), @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlGetSelfStatus(), @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSetPeerStatus() and @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlGetPeerStatus() @n
   3066              Set and get flow control status of self or peer device. Note that the return
   3067              value from these two functions depends on the flow control mode set by
   3068              @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet(), @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), or
   3069              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart().
   3070          
   3071             @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlIgnoreRestrain() @n
   3072              Enables transmission when restrained by flow control.
   3073          
   3074             @ref UARTDRV_PauseTransmit() and @ref UARTDRV_ResumeTransmit() @n
   3075              Pause a currently active transmit operation by preventing the DMA from loading
   3076              the UART FIFO. Will not override HW flow control state (if applicable), but
   3077              can be used in conjunction.
   3078          
   3079             @n @section uartdrv_fc Flow Control Support
   3080          
   3081             If UART flow control is not required, make sure that
   3082             EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE is set to 0. This reduces the code size
   3083             and complexity of the driver.
   3084          
   3085             Both hardware and software flow control are supported. To
   3086             enable either of these, set EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE to 1 in
   3087             uartdrv_config.h.
   3088          
   3089             @n @subsection uartdrv_fc_hw Hardware Flow Control
   3090          
   3091             UART hardware flow control uses two additional pins for flow control
   3092             handshaking, the clear-to-send (CTS) and ready-to-send (RTS) pins.
   3093             RTS is an output and CTS is an input. These are active-low signals.
   3094             When CTS is high, the UART transmitter should stop sending frames.
   3095             A receiver should set RTS high when it is no longer capable of
   3096             receiving data.
   3097          
   3098             @par Peripheral Hardware Flow Control
   3099          
   3100             Newer devices natively support CTS/RTS in
   3101             the USART peripheral hardware. To enable hardware flow control, perform the
   3102             following steps:
   3103          
   3104             - Set EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE to 1.
   3105             - In the @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t struct passed to @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), set
   3106              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlHwUart.
   3107             - Define the pins for CTS and RTS by setting ctsPort, ctsPin, rtsPort
   3108              and rtsPin in the init struct.
   3109             - Also define the CTS and RTS locations by setting portLocationCts and
   3110              portLocationRts in the init struct.
   3111          
   3112             @par GPIO Hardware Flow Control
   3113          
   3114             To support hardware flow control on devices that don't have UART CTS/RTS
   3115             hardware support, the driver includes the sl_gpio driver to emulate a
   3116             hardware implementation of UART CTS/RTS flow control on these devices.
   3117          
   3118             To enable hardware flow control, perform the following steps:
   3119          
   3120             - Set EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE to 1.
   3121             - UART/USART: In the @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t struct passed to
   3122              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), set
   3123              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlHw.
   3124             - LEUART: In the @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t struct passed to
   3125              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart(), set
   3126              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlHw.
   3127             - Define the pins for CTS and RTS by setting ctsPort, ctsPin, rtsPort and
   3128              rtsPin in the same init struct.
   3129          
   3130             @note Because of the limitations in GPIO interrupt hardware, you cannot select
   3131             CTS pins in multiple driver instances with the same pin number. For example, pin A0 and
   3132             B0 cannot serve as CTS pins in two concurrent driver instances.
   3133          
   3134             RTS is set high whenever there are no Rx operations queued. The UART
   3135             transmitter is halted when the CTS pin goes high. The transmitter completes
   3136             the current frame before halting. DMA transfers are also halted.
   3137          
   3138             @n @subsection uartdrv_fc_sw Software Flow Control
   3139          
   3140             UART software flow control uses in-band signaling, meaning the receiver sends
   3141             special flow control characters to the transmitter and thereby removes
   3142             the need for dedicated wires for flow control. The two symbols
   3143             UARTDRV_FC_SW_XON and UARTDRV_FC_SW_XOFF are defined in uartdrv_config.h.
   3144          
   3145             To enable support for software flow control, perform the following steps:
   3146          
   3147             - Set EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE to 1.
   3148             - UART/USART: In the @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t structure passed to
   3149              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), set
   3150              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlSw.
   3151             - LEUART: In the @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t structure passed to
   3152              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart(), set
   3153              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlSw.
   3154          
   3155             @note Software flow control is partial only.
   3156          
   3157             The application must monitor buffers and make decisions on when to send XON/
   3158             XOFF. XON/XOFF can be sent to the peer using @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet().
   3159             Though @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet() will pause the active transmit operation
   3160             to send a flow control character, there is no way to guarantee the order.
   3161             If the application implements a specific packet format where the flow control
   3162             codes may appear only in fixed positions, the application should not
   3163             use @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet() but implement read and write of XON/XOFF
   3164             into packet buffers. If the application code fully implements all the flow
   3165             control logic, EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE should be set to 0
   3166             to reduce code space.
   3167          
   3168             @n @section uartdrv_example Example
   3169             @if DOXYDOC_P1_DEVICE
   3170              @if DOXYDOC_EFM32G
   3171              @include uartdrv_example_p1_nomvdis.c
   3172              @endif
   3173              @if DOXYDOC_EZR32HG
   3174              @include uartdrv_example_p1_usart0.c
   3175              @endif
   3176              @ifnot (DOXYDOC_EFM32G || DOXYDOC_EZR32HG)
   3177              @include uartdrv_example_p1.c
   3178              @endif
   3179             @endif
   3180             @if DOXYDOC_P2_DEVICE
   3181             @include uartdrv_example_p2.c
   3182             @endif
   3183             @if DOXYDOC_S2_DEVICE
   3184             @include uartdrv_example_s2.c
   3185             @endif
   3186          
   3187           * @} end group uartdrv *********************************************************/

